# Backend C# — Critical Rules Summary

Full convention guides are in `docs/conventions/backend/`. Read the relevant file before editing a layer. This file is a quick reference only.

## Ten Critical Rules

### 1. Sealed by Default

All concrete classes and records MUST be `sealed` unless the type is explicitly a base class.

```csharp
// GOOD:
sealed class CreatePostCommandHandler : ICommandHandler<CreatePostCommand, PostId> { }

// BAD:
class CreatePostCommandHandler : ICommandHandler<CreatePostCommand, PostId> { }
```

### 2. No Controllers - IEndpoint Only

Never create a class that inherits from `ControllerBase` or `Controller`. All HTTP endpoints MUST implement `IEndpoint`.

```csharp
// GOOD:
sealed class CreatePostEndpoint : IEndpoint
{
    public void MapEndpoint(IEndpointRouteBuilder app) { ... }
}

// BAD:
[ApiController]
[Route("api/posts")]
class PostsController : ControllerBase { }
```

### 3. No Aggregate Loading in Query Handlers

Query handlers MUST inject `IXxxReadStore`, not `IXxxRepository`.

```csharp
// GOOD:
sealed class GetPostByIdQueryHandler : IQueryHandler<GetPostByIdQuery, PostResult>
{
    public GetPostByIdQueryHandler(IPostReadStore postReadStore) { ... }
}

// BAD:
sealed class GetPostByIdQueryHandler : IQueryHandler<GetPostByIdQuery, PostResult>
{
    public GetPostByIdQueryHandler(IPostRepository postRepository) { ... }
}
```

### 4. Correct Exception Hierarchy

See `docs/conventions/backend/06-exception-hierarchy.md`. Validators throw `ApplicationValidationException` subclasses. Repositories throw `AggregateNotFoundException` subclasses. Aggregates throw `DomainException` subclasses. Never throw `InvalidOperationException` or `ArgumentException` in domain or application code.

### 5. CancellationToken on All Async Methods

The last parameter of every async method MUST be named exactly `cancellationToken`.

```csharp
// GOOD:
Task<PostResult> HandleAsync(GetPostByIdQuery query, CancellationToken cancellationToken);

// BAD:
Task<PostResult> HandleAsync(GetPostByIdQuery query, CancellationToken ct);
```

### 6. No Handlers or Validators in Contracts Projects

`Application.Write.Contracts` and `Application.Read.Contracts` contain only records and interfaces. Handlers and validators belong in the implementation projects.

### 7. No External Libraries in Application.Reactions

Event handlers define narrow interfaces for external capabilities. Infrastructure implements those interfaces. The Reactions project MUST NOT reference EF Core, email clients, HTTP clients, or any similar external library.

### 8. Named cancellationToken Parameter

The `CancellationToken` parameter MUST be named `cancellationToken`, not `ct`, `token`, or `cancel`.

### 9. AwesomeAssertions in Tests

All test assertions use AwesomeAssertions. The API surface is identical to FluentAssertions.

```csharp
// GOOD:
post.State.Should().BeOfType<PublishedPostState>();

// BAD:
Assert.IsType<PublishedPostState>(post.State);
```

### 10. Mermaid for All Diagrams

All diagrams in documentation files MUST use Mermaid syntax in a fenced code block. No ASCII art.
